ionRevisions","id":"94711","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/94711"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 24-year-old man is brought to the Emergency Department after being retrieved from a rollover of his quad bike which landed on top of him. He has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he clearly has multiple injuries, is in pain and is having difficulty breathing. His pulse rate is 110/min, blood pressure 100/60 mmHg, respiratory rate 28/min, SpO2 88% on room air, and temperature 36.5\u00b0C. Primary survey reveals extensive bruising over his left chest wall and paradoxical respiration. The trachea is midline and chest auscultation reveals bilateral breath sounds. His Glasgow Coma Scale score is E1 V2 M4 (total 7).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate next step in management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Needle thoracotomy","Trauma series X-rays","Underwater seal chest drain","Chest wall support binder","Endotracheal intubation"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis man is in respiratory failure as evidenced by his respiratory distress, paradoxical breathing, and deteriorating status. The common causes of respiratory compromise after chest wall trauma are pneumothorax, haemothorax, flail chest, and pulmonary contusion. The management of the trauma in an emergency setting should follow the ABCD scheme (ie, airway, breathing, circulation, disability). If the suspicion for tension pneumothorax is high then occasionally \u0022breathing\u0022 takes precedence to \u0022airway\u0022 as intubation to manage airway can lead to exacerbation of pneumothorax whereas release of the tension with a \u003Cstrong\u003Eneedle thoracotomy\u003C/strong\u003E or \u003Cstrong\u003Eunderwater seal chest drain\u003C/strong\u003E can be life saving. However, this patient has a midline trachea and bilateral breath sounds which make the diagnosis of pneumothorax less likely. Paradoxical breathing suggests a flail chest, with multiple rib fractures and pulmonary contusion. He has compromised respiration and is deteriorating. He is likely to rapidly lose his airway and the most immediate step taken should be the maintenance of a patent airway and ventilation. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA typical rule of thumb in trauma is that a GCS of at least 8 is required to maintain airway patency. Hence, he requires prompt \u003Cstrong\u003Eendotracheal intubation\u003C/strong\u003E and ventilation. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EFurther imaging, \u003Cstrong\u003Esuch as trauma series X-rays\u003C/strong\u003E, to characterise other injuries should wait until after his airway is secured. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA \u003Cstrong\u003Echest wall support binder\u003C/strong\u003E might be of value to reduce painful chest wall movement after an injury, but would have no place in the initial management of this patient.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["In trauma situations, priority must always be given to ensuring satisfactory airway protection.","A Glasgow Coma Scale (GCS) score of 8 or less indicates a need for immediate airway intervention.","Flail chest with paradoxical breathing indicates severe chest wall injury requiring prompt respiratory support."],"references":["Richter T, Ragaller M. Ventilation in chest trauma. J Emerg Trauma Shock. 2011;4(2):251-9. Available at: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC3132366/","Avva U, Lata JM, Hendrix JM, et al. Airway Management. [Updated 2025 Jan 19]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2025 Jan-. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK470403/","Overbeck MC. Airway Management of Respiratory Failure. Emerg Med Clin North Am. 2016 Feb;34(1):97-127. doi: 10.1016/j.emc.2015.08.007. PMID: 26614244. Available from: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/26614244/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"77744"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1701"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"77744","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/77744"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-03-25T10:54:10+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-03-25T10:57:00+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1701"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"94711"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"11","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/11"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udec1","name":"Respiratory Medicine","synonyms":["Pulmonology"],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"24","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/24"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\ude91","name":"Emergency Medicine","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"5"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"26","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/26"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udd7c","name":"Critical Care Medicine","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"5"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"66","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/66"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Management","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{